<TEXT>
two of the nations largest farm lobbying 
groups are giving widely divergent pictures of american farming if 
president bush prevails in his quest to eliminate all 
tradedistorting crop subsidies 
for the national farmers union an end to subsidies would turn 
back the clock to the depression where farmers were whipsawed by 
boombust cycles of overproduction and shortages 
but the american farm bureau federation has a less apocalyptic 
view believing us farmers will be able to adapt to a 
subsidyfree global market 
last weeks economic summit in houston produced an agreement of 
sorts that white house officials hope will breathe new life into 
the ongoing uruguay round trade talks in geneva 
the united states wants the 97member general agreement on 
tariffs and trade to eliminate export subsidies on agricultural 
products and to start winding down internal farm subsidies on food 
production 
but us officials insist there will be no unilateral scuttling 
of farm programs and bush made it clear that he will not ask 
congress to dismantle us farm subsidies unless other countries do 
likewise 
spending for commodity programs under the 1985 farm law which 
expires this year is estimated at 794 billion over five years 
the cost of the 1990 farm bill is projected at about 55 billion 
the national farmers union supports the us proposal for 
eliminating export subsidies spokesman bob denman said export 
subsidies are paid so that one countrys commodities can have a 
price edge on those of another 
the 12nation european community is a major user of export 
subsidies for agricultural products and the united states in 
recent years has retaliated with subsidies of its own called the 
export enhancement program 
aside from that the nfu is wary about trading away the 
traditional us price supports for wheat corn cotton rice milk 
and other products 
without domestic farm programs the programs the president 
wants ended i predict a return to depressionera supply and price 
cycles massive overproduction and waste of foodstuffs says nfu 
president leland swenson 
don lipton a spokesman for the american farm bureau federation 
has a milder view 
we think we will continue to have a safety net of price 
supports lipton said but pressed to comment on the possibility of 
all being phased out he said american farmers are competitive 
enough to survive and do well 
they will flourish in competing for new markets lipton 
said in a few areas we might have some problems but therell 
be enough time to make adjustments to become competitive 
most american farmers he said realize that they should be 
assuming more of the risks of production and not rely so much on 
the government 
yet in the 1990 farm bill its clear that theres not going 
to be any great shift in that direction in the near term lipton 
said 
agriculture secretary clayton yeutter said the houston agreement 
reaffirmed a goal of longterm agricultural policy reform and 
emphasized the uruguay round as a step in that direction 
there was an intent expressed in houston to reduce each 
countrys farm supports which have a tendency to stimulate 
excess production he said 
yeutter said another objective is to have specific 
negotiations on reducing and hopefully phasing out export 
subsidies throughout the world 
a third objective is to open trade doors the houston agreement 
yeutter said contained considerable language that tells the 
world the uruguay round of trade talks is important and that time 
is running out 
but phasing out domestic price supports even if the other gatt 
countries agree to do the same 
rep dan glickman dkan chairman of the house agriculture 
subcommittee on wheat soybeans and feed grains thinks its a pipe 
dream 
we may be in an era of somewhat reduced international export 
subsidies glickman said but its pie in the sky to say were 
going to eliminate domestic subsidies i just dont think thats 
going to happen the cycle of history is kind of immutable 
rep dante fascell dfla chairman of the house foreign 
affairs committee said after listening to bush last week that it 
would be hard to sell the idea on capitol hill 
if you follow the history of farm price supports in this 
country its been very difficult to conclude anything except that 
farm subsidies will live forever fascell said 
house speaker thomas s foley dwash a former agriculture 
committee chairman said the europeans have great reluctance to 
dismantle farm subsidies and those he said go far beyond the 
us programs 
one of the us criticisms of the european agricultural 
structure is that there are far too many small mom and pop farms 
and subsidies have been designed to preserve them 
in the united states farm programs have been keyed to 
production since their roots were set in the early 1930s 
as a result the larger a farm is the more it produces the 
larger the subsidies in 1988 for example about 633000 farms 
received federal subsidy payments averaging 14257 each according 
to the general accounting office the investigative arm of congress 
more than 70 percent of the total payments in 1988 went to farms 
that grossed more than 100000 a year that included 136 percent 
of the total to 21701 farmers whose annual sales were 500000 or 
more an average of 56571 each 
by comparison 159691 farms averaged 10917 each making up 
less than 20 percent of the years subsidy payments 
advocates of targeting payments to smaller farmers are aiming at 
further action when 1990 farm legislation comes up for floor debate 
in the house the week of july 23 
the charge is led by reps richard armey rtexas and charles 
schumer dny who want to eliminate subsidies to any producer 
with income over 100000 a year or with gross sales of more than 
500000 
</TEXT>
