<TEXT>
bereft of its empire and wrestling with the 
prospect of a reunited germany dominating europe britain has once 
again become embroiled in a dispute over its commitment to european 
political and economic union 
its an issue that has caused four cabinet ministers to leave 
prime minister margaret thatchers government in four years and 
is expected to dominate british politics through the 1990s 
prime minister margaret thatchers opposition to european 
political and economic union is wellknown especially now that 
germany is uniting 
thus when nicholas ridley her ideological soulmate and closest 
cabinet colleague launched a diatribe against the germans and the 
european community bureaucracy it provoked new questions about 
mrs thatchers true feelings 
in an interview in last weeks spectator magazine ridley 
accused germany of seeking to dominate a federal europe called 
france a poodle of west germany and said that surrendering 
british sovereignty to unelected european community politicians was 
tantamount to giving it to hitler 
facing a chorus of disapproval from the opposition as well as 
his own conservative party ridley resigned as trade secretary on 
saturday 
on sunday it emerged that mrs thatcher called a meeting of 
leading academics in march to discuss germany the talk touched 
among other things on german stereotypes like bullying egotism 
and sentimentality 
it was a further embarrassment to a government already on the 
defensive over ridleys remarks 
polls in several sunday papers found about half of all britons 
disagreeing with ridley 53 percent in the sunday telegraph poll 
52 percent in the sunday correspondent and 48 percent in the sunday 
times 
the independent on sunday published the leaked text of a summary 
of the academics meeting written by charles powell mrs 
thatchers private secretary this guaranteed that the issue of 
europe would remain on top of the national agenda 
the summary of the march 24 meeting at mrs thatchers country 
home said even the optimists had some unease not for the present 
and the immediate future but for what might lie further down the 
road than we can yet see 
