arguments about britains commitment to the european community 
have bedeviled mrs thatchers cabinet in recent years 
michael heseltine quit as defense secretary in 1986 after losing 
a battle over the sale of an ailing british helicopter 
manufacturer heseltine favored selling it to a european 
consortium mrs thatcher preferred an american buyer 
heseltines resignation forced home secretary leon brittan to 
quit 
the longrunning argument about britains entry into the 
arrangement that acts to stabilize european community currencies 
the exchange rate mechanism was in the background of another 
upheaval last year 
geoffrey howe then foreign secretary and a supporter of the 
mechanism was demoted months later nigel lawson resigned as 
treasury chief in a dispute linked to it 
britains entry into the currency arrangement now looks 
inevitable but a whole new issue has loomed the uniting of the 
12 european community nations under a single currency and central 
bank 
economic union combined with a lifting of border controls and 
tariffs is planned for jan 1 1993 and mrs thatcher loathes the 
idea seeing it as the end of britains sovereignty over its 
economic affairs 
these are complex financial affairs above the heads of many 
britons but ridleys blunt remarks in the spectator interview 
about monetary union being all a german racket designed to take 
over the whole of europe were much more readily understandable 
they ensure that europe as a british political issue will run 
and run 
