<TEXT>
the district of columbia spent almost four 
times the national average on criminal and civil justice in 1988 
the year it became the nations murder capital according to a 
justice department report 
the city spent about 859 per resident that year for justice 
systems including police protection the courts and correctional 
facilities the national average per capita spending on justice 
activities by state and local governments that year was 218 the 
state that spent the least per capita was west virginia which 
spent only about 90 per person 
sue lindgren the statistician who prepared the report released 
sunday by the bureau of justice statistics speculated that the 
nations capital topped the per capita spending on justice because 
the entire district is an urban center 
we know theres more crime in high population density areas 
than in rural areas she said 
washington dc became the nations murder capital in 1988 an 
unwanted unofficial title it maintained last year as well 
the second highest per capita spending by state and local 
governments on justice activities in 1988 was in alaska 541 
followed by new york 399 california 316 and nevada 315 
rounding out the top 10 were arizona 276 new jersey 274 
hawaii 249 massachusetts 246 and delaware 240 
those states spending the least after west virginia were 
arkansas 97 mississippi 100 north dakota 106 south dakota 
116 indiana 124 iowa 125 montana 130 idaho 132 and 
kentucky 133 
federal state and local governments spent a total of 61 
billion two years ago for civil and criminal justice 
of that total almost 46 percent or about 28 billion was 
spent on police protection another 31 percent was spent on 
corrections and about 22 percent was spent on courts prosecution 
and legal services and public defenders 
local governments contributed 335 billion or 55 percent of 
the money spent on justice systems state governments spent 221 
billion or 33 percent and the federal government spent 78 
billion or 12 percent 
in the decade from 1979 through 1988 total spending on justice 
systems increased by 1343 percent 
however the real increase for the decade was 214 percent when 
the dollars are adjusted for inflation the report said 
the constant dollar spending amounted to a 65 percent increase 
during the decade in corrections spending 34 percent increases in 
prosecution legal services and public defense a 17 percent hike 
in courts and a 3 percent increase in police protection 
justice systems received 32 percent of all government spending 
two years ago the federal government devoted the smallest portion 
of its expenditures for justice 07 percent states spent 61 
percent of their money for such activities and cities allocated 68 
percent of their funds for justice the report said 
