<TEXT>
heartattack patients who are advised to 
quit smoking on leaving the hospital appear to have better success 
when they get periodic telephone calls of encouragement from 
nurses researchers say 
of the 72 heartattack patients who completed a nursemanaged 
intervention program by stanford university 51 of them or 71 
percent successfully quit smoking for one year stanford 
researchers reported in sundays annals of internal medicine 
of the 58 patients who did not get calls only 26 of them or 45 
percent had cut out tobacco the study found 
many quitsmoking programs attack both the psychological and the 
biological addiction to nicotine but some smokers benefit from 
additional outside help the researchers said 
nurses represent the largest cadre of health care 
professionals available to assist physicians with interventions for 
smoking cessation wrote the researchers led by dr c barr 
taylor 
dr steven cummings of the university of california at san 
francisco who studies physicians attitudes and training on 
smoking cessation programs said the stanford study demonstrates 
that phone calls are an effective way of providing support to 
smokers trying to quit 
the nursemanaged program usually began one day after patients 
left the hospitals coronary care unit smokers were given manuals 
and audio tapes on cessation techniques and counseling while 
hospitalized nurses then followed up on the care by calling 
patients weekly for one month and then monthly for the next four 
months 
patients who found it more difficult to quit met with nurses in 
an outpatient clinic and some received prescriptions for nicotine 
gum the nurses intervention ended after six months 
the researchers verified the volunteers smoking status through 
biochemical tests or through family members and friends 
the researchers attributed the success of the intervention 
program to the early start while patients were hospitalized and the 
frequent and convenient contact between patients and nurses 
smoking is blamed for the deaths of 390000 americans each year 
according to federal statistics about 13 million smokers quit 
every year but about 1 million start smoking 
</TEXT>
