<TEXT>
japan which has moved from the secondlargest 
world bank loan debtor to the worlds largest creditor nation 
repaid its last world bank loan today 
the last 7 million installment on a 25year 75 million loan 
to the japan highway public corp was paid said world bank 
spokeswoman keiko sato 
between 1953 and 1966 japan borrowed 8629 million from the 
world bank to finance 31 projects only india borrowed more money 
from the world bank at that time 
the loans financed the construction of power plants steel mills 
and other development projects 
the world bank provided money during japans roughest times 
said seiichiro yonekura professor of business history at 
hitotsubashi university 
without its help japans postwar recovery would have been 
inconceivable the banks strict scrutiny over borrowers also 
forced japanese companies to improve their management and 
accounting practices yonekura said 
in a statement released by the world bank j burke knapp 
chairman of the banks loan committee during the 1950s and 1960s 
said there was considerable skepticism in the bank regarding 
japans economic viability and creditworthiness 
when the bank awarded its first loans to japan the economy was 
in an almost primitive condition barely recovered from the 
ravages of war and struggling with seemingly intractable 
balanceofpayments problems he said 
but burke knapp added that when japan stopped borrowing from the 
world bank in 1966 the world bank too had cause to regret the 
termination since for many years we had been saying that every 
loan we made to japan improved the quality of our general 
portfolio 
japan is now the second largest contributor after the united 
states to the international loan institution bearing 669 percent 
of its total shares the bank also borrows up to onethird of its 
finances from the tokyo money market 
the united states lost its position as worlds largest creditor 
nation to japan in the early 1980s by 1985 the united states was 
a net debtor for the first time in 71 years 
in 1989 the united states tightened its grip on the title of 
worlds largest debtor by ending the year with a net debt of 6637 
billion up 25 percent from the previous year 
