<TEXT>
us presidents have for four decades relied 
on cia assessments of the soviet economy that vastly overstate the 
economic strength of americas chief rival witnesses told a senate 
committee monday 
sen daniel patrick moynihan dny said the faulty numbers 
could well have created an unjustified level of concern about 
soviet strength that in turn led the united states to overspend on 
defense 
the cia has come to be relied upon as the principal western 
source of information about the soviet economy including its 
overall gross national product and the proportion of the gnp 
devoted to military might 
the spy agency has rated soviet economic growth as higher than 
that of the united states for most of the period since it began its 
assessments in the early 1950s last year the cia put the soviet 
gnp at 51 percent of the us gnp of 523 trillion 
that figure puts the cia near the top of a range of estimates 
which go as low as 14 percent and moynihan said a more realistic 
number would be around 33 percent if we had kept with that 
onethird number we would have behaved differently moynihan 
said 
michael boskin chairman of the presidents council of economic 
advisers said the onethird figure is probably a good estimate 
the spy agencys chief analyst of the soviet union george kolt 
conceded the agencys number is probably too high but maintained 
we have done a good job on a very complex issue 
kolt said the cia would adjust its figures downward perhaps 
nearer to an economic growth of 35 percent if it can get better 
information on the quality of soviet goods and can improve its own 
analytical methods 
but he said the agencys estimates have been accurate when it 
comes to soviet defense spending 
boskin pointed out that any estimates of the soviet economy are 
made difficult because of problems in getting accurate data about 
production and consumption the inability to compare currencies and 
the fundamental problem of assigning value to items in a system 
without market pricing 
the process is fraught with distortions such as the soviet 
plant that produces an excess of easytomake ball bearings then 
ships them to a steel mill where they are melted down and sent back 
to make more bearings boskin said 
moynihan pointed out that it is difficult as well for 
americans to conceive of a system where fully onehalf of 
agricultural production can be lost to spoilage because of a 
defective distribution system 
those difficulties will confront the international monetary fund 
when it seeks to carry out a study of the soviet economy mandated 
last week by the worlds seven most developed nations the imf 
study is to be the basis for any future aid to the soviet union 
congress ran into its own problems in trying to assess the cias 
performance a witness from the general accounting office allan 
mendelowitz said he had been stymied by the agency in seeking 
information for a congressionally mandated study of cia methodology 
this is discouraging moynihan said promising to take the 
matter up with cia director william webster didnt i read 
somewhere that the cold war is over 
</TEXT>
