monopoly 
mikhail f nenashev the chief of gostelradio and a communist 
party traditionalist said in an interview broadcast on soviet tv 
that the decree issued by gorbachev sunday will make managing 
television much more complex than in the past 
gorbachevs presidential decree on democratization of 
television and radio is designed to cut back on the communist 
partys monopoly on the airwaves 
the decree recognizes the need to determine a legal basis for 
the activities of television and radio broadcasting under new 
conditions and recommended that parliament adopt appropriate 
laws apparently corresponding to the press law passed june 12 
that law gave nongovernment and nonparty groups the right to 
own and operate newspapers and magazines ending what effectively 
had been a decadesold monopoly held by communist authorities 
growing democracy within the country requires a cardinal 
change in the nature of the countrys television and radio 
broadcasting said the decree which also was carried by the 
state news agency tass 
the guidelines for radio and television currently are set by a 
state committee 
until now only groups approved by the committee had access to 
soviet television as a result the communist party received large 
segments of time on the airwaves 
the decree emphasized the inadmissibility of monopolizing air 
time by this or that party political current or group tass 
reported 
for a lasting time the television was under the party 
influence what we used to call and still call the party 
monopoly said nenashev who formerly held the post of head of 
the state publishing committee 
