<TEXT>
an israeli human rights group accused soldiers 
of an itchy trigger finger in dealing with the palestinian 
uprising and said monday that unclear firing orders resulted in 
hundreds of unnecessary deaths 
the army spokesmans office criticized the 60page report by 
betselem saying it contains many inconsistencies and was 
haughty incriminating and onesided 
the office refused to discuss specific charges saying it could 
not comment until the supreme court rules on a suit filed this year 
challenging the armys orders in the occupied territories 
according to figures compiled by the associated press israeli 
soldiers or civilians have killed 723 palestinians during the 
31monthold rebellion against israeli occupation of the west bank 
and gaza strip 
an additional 236 palestinians were killed by fellow arabs most 
on suspicion of collaboration with israeli authorities fortyfive 
israelis have died in the violence 
the betselem report said shootings by soldiers accounted for 
the overwhelming majority of fatalities and that there were 
hundreds of cases in which death could have been averted 
it blamed unclear firing regulations saying they led to a 
tangle of interpretations on when and how weapons can be used 
betselem also known as the israeli information center for human 
rights in the occupied territories was founded by liberal israeli 
legislators academics and lawyers to investigate human rights 
problems in the occupied lands amnesty international is among the 
international groups which have cited its findings 
the facts evoke an image of an itchy trigger finger a lax 
observance of regulations the absence of exhaustive investigations 
and a failure to mete out deterring and educational punishment 
betselem reported 
it said these suggest legitimacy is conferred on unjustified 
firing and violation of the law 
the report was especially critical of army handling of 
palestinian demonstrations in which most deaths have occurred 
army orders require soldiers to fire at a demonstrators legs 
and to shoot to kill only if the soldiers life is threatened 
the report said just one of the nine soldiers killed during the 
uprising died during a riot 
these figures show that no direct correlation exists between 
the intensity of the danger to life and the circumstances in which 
soldiers may open fire it said 
it also criticized army use of plastic bullets for punishment 
and deterrence calling this an extremely grave and wholly 
improper usage 
the army introduced plastic bullets in july 1988 trying to 
reduce fatalities it says the bullets are not lethal when fired 
from at least 230 feet 
betselem said at least 128 palestinians have been killed with 
plastic ammunition 
brig gen amnon strasnov the armys chief legal officer told 
israel radio the army takes every step to decrease the number of 
deaths and injuries and said plastic bullets resulted in a 
significant decrease in deaths 
he noted that 122 soldiers have faced courtsmartial proceedings 
during the uprising 41 for illegal killing causing death or 
illegal use of firearms most were found guilty he said 
but betselem said only two soldiers have been tried for 
manslaughter during the uprising 
dedi zucker a founder of betselem and a parliament member from 
the leftwing citizens rights movement told a news conference in 
tel aviv on sunday the findings suggest the army should adopt 
regulations closer to those used by police 
police must exhaust nonlethal riot controls measures such as 
tear gas and rubber bullets and face lifethreatening situations 
before they can get commanders permission to fire lethal weapons 
zucker observed that jerusalem is under police jurisdiction he 
noted it has seen considerably less violence and fewer people 
killed than towns in the west bank and gaza where the army 
functions 
he said the police have adopted totally different criteria 
and with much more success the army should adopt the police 
criteria 
</TEXT>
