<TEXT>
a whale that got tangled in a 
fishing net was freed monday by scientists who rushed to its aid 
aboard a flotilla of research boats and private craft 
its swimming free into the sunset said tom hill captain 
of the yankee captains out of gloucester as the 25ton mammal 
spouted and splashed out into the open sea 
the fiveyearold 40footlong humpback had been tangled for 
most of the day in a fishing net 
the humpback nicknamed mallard by whale watchers was 
discovered thrashing in the water 17 miles off massachusetts 
rescuers could clearly hear trumpeting through the breathing 
hole atop its head as it fought the net and rope running through 
its mouth and around its body 
its a sign of antagonism or anxiety scientist steven 
frohock said of the sound as he waited with others for the whale to 
tire so it could be approached 
rescue workers attached buoys to the trailing ends of the net 
wrapped around mallard hoping the additional drag would tire the 
whale forcing it to rest on the surface 
thirty to 40 other whales humpbacks and finbacks circled and 
fed in the area keeping a safe distance from the boats but one 
whale apparently hearing mallards cries came up along side the 
entangled mammal and rubbed its head 
leading a crew of four rescuers late in the afternoon charles 
stormy mayo head of the center for coastal studies in 
provincetown mass approached the whales in two inflatable 
motorboats a few minutes before 5 pm after more than an hour of 
effort they managed to free mallard from the plastic net at one 
point mayos boat nearly overturned when mallard reared its head 
mayo clad in a wetsuit got into the water at one point a risky 
move 
hill a 10year veteran of whalewatching trips said the 
rescuers would only in the most extreme circumstances get into the 
water to help the whale 
one swoop of a flipper and they could be dead he said 
the whale was caught in a gill net set along the seafloor on the 
stellwagen bank to catch tuna and other fish 
the area is frequented by whalewatching boats of by 
massachusetts companies that earn their keep by taking humans to 
watch their animal cousins feed and frolic rather than harpooning 
them as in the old days 
the mission set off monday from gloucester and across cape cod 
bay from provincetown mass after a fisherman radioed that he was 
awakened in the morning by a whale thrashing next to his boat the 
whale first recorded by whale watchers in 1986 was identified by 
scars and coloring on its tail and flukes or flippers 
mallard was the second tangled whale sighted in a week last 
week a whale known as quixote was spotted trailing net which the 
whales hit when diving to the bottom in search of the same fish the 
nets are designed to ensnare quixote hadnt been seen since 
thursday 
its a very precarious situation these whales arent very 
happy to have a boat on top of them said frohock chief 
scientist of yankee fleet one of the whalewatching companies 
when they start thrashing around it can be a lifeanddeath 
situation not only for the whale but also for the people trying 
to save him 
the whale sex unknown was tangled in one of the 
quartermilelong gill nets set on the stellwagen bank which is 
about 17 miles off gloucester and 25 miles from provincetown the 
bank is 25 miles long five miles wide has an average depth of 84 
feet 
the area is a prime fishing ground this time of year for tuna 
but it is also where fishermen catch haddock pollock codfish and 
some of the smaller species of whiting and red fish whales too 
come there for about half the year to feed 
lt glenn miller the us coast guards fisheries coordination 
officer in boston described gill nets as similar to freestanding 
chainlink fence about eight feet height and sitting on the ocean 
floor the bottom edge is weighted with lead and the upper edge has 
plastic floats to keep the net upright 
