the justice department will pay 25000 to a 
former official cleared of espionage allegations to head off a 
lawsuit over an erroneous report about the inquiry a lawyer said 
monday 
matthew l myers who represents former justice department 
official roger pilon said the government issued a private letter 
of apology last week and agreed to pay 25000 to settle the 
dispute 
pilon former director of the justice departments asylum policy 
and review unit was placed on administrative leave in 1988 when he 
and his wife juliana were investigated to determine whether they 
had passed a classified document to south african diplomats 
the investigation did not result in criminal charges and pilon 
was reinstated in his job and his topsecret security clearance was 
restored 
but the 1988 annual report of the departments internal watchdog 
unit described a different outcome when it was issued last fall 
the report by the office of professional responsibility which 
did not identify pilon by name said that the investigation found 
sufficient cause to terminate the officialss appointment 
the employee resigned prior to the initiation of removal 
proceedings said the report 
pilon acknowledged to reporters who had learned his name that he 
was the person referred to in the report but denied any wrongdoing 
he demanded an apology from the justice department which conducted 
a further inquiry into the matter 
in its july 12 letter the justice department acknowledged that 
there was confusion created by the publication of the opr 
report last fall 
assistant attorney general stuart m gerson said in the letter 
that the pilons were entitled to an apology because the 1988 
investigation of mr pilon did not produce any evidence sufficient 
to warrant his dismissal from the department 
gerson noted that pilon was restored unconditionally to his 
agency position and his subsequent resignation was selfinitiated 
and was not made in the face of removal proceedings which in fact 
never had been contemplated or ordered 
as part of the settlement gersons letter will be placed in 
justice department files along with those at the state department 
the fbi and the national security agency 
pilon said he suspects that the investigation may have begun 
after the nsa intercepted a conversation between his wife and a 
south african diplomat in new york 
at the time mrs pilon was analyzing un policies for the 
heritage foundation 
pilon says he suspects his wifes conversation with the diplomat 
was misinterpreted by eavesdroppers 
according to a chronology of the case released by pilons 
lawyer the couple were interrogated separately but simultaneously 
on jan 6 1988 by the fbi 
the pilons have maintained that the probe cost mrs pilon a 
presidential nomination to be an assistant secretary of interior 
the pilons have denied that they gave a classified state 
department report on the influence of communism in south africa to 
a south african diplomat in new york 
the fbi told the pilons they had both showed problems when 
they took polygraph tests according to the chronology but the 
couple both passed polygraph tests administered by private 
investigators 
during the investigation the chronology said the fbi agents 
told the pilons they had a high degree of confidence that the 
pilons transmitted the document and that they had other 
evidence 
but on sept 9 1988 associate deputy attorney general dee v 
benson reinstated pilon and said in a letter that no implication 
adverse to you should be taken from the investigations 
myers said the pilons had threatened to file suit unless the 
department acted decisively to correct the record and to compensate 
the pilons 
in many respects the admission of error is too little too 
late there is no reason this should have taken eight months to 
resolve when the facts are as clear as they are myers said 
