<TEXT>
from coventry to philadelphia from the edge 
of harlem to the golden gate cathedral building in the 20th 
century has often been accompanied by controversy 
a cathedral serves as the official seat or chair of the bishop 
of a diocese in churches that are governed by bishops such as the 
roman catholic eastern orthodox anglican or episcopal and in 
sweden the lutheran denominations 
the question of whether and how to build cathedrals has been 
revived with the scheduled completion in september of the 
gothicstyle washington national cathedral begun in 1907 the 
question is not a new one 
when the 14th century st michaels cathedral in coventry 
england was gutted by german bombing during world war ii the 
cathedral chapter decided to rebuild in a controversial modern 
style 
i think they were right said stanford lehmberg a historian 
of cathedrals who teaches at the university of minnesota arguing 
that england already has a wealth of real medieval churches and 
doesnt need to build copies here where we dont genuinely have 
any medieval buildings i think it is appropriate for us to have 
one 
san francisco roman catholics however built a modern cathedral 
after their 75yearold red brick gothic one was destroyed by fire 
in 1962 
the community at large expected the new cathedral to be a 
building of the future not a clever replica of a traditional 
style monsignor james p gaffey said in a lecture in 1983 
some didnt want it to be built at all 
twentyseven priests wrote to archbishop joseph t mcgucken in 
1967 that human inequities must take precedence over parish and 
diocesan building programs 
the archbishop argued there was no contradiction between 
building a cathedral and helping the poor the new st marys 
cathedral was dedicated in 1971 
in 1967 episcopal bishop horace w donegan of new york halted 
fundraising to complete the cathedral church of st john the 
divine begun in 1892 he said the structure located on the border 
of harlem would remain unfinished as a witness to the despair 
and anguish of the nearby slums 
this decision was reversed by bishop paul moore in the 1970s 
work has resumed and a fundraising drive is under way aimed at 
completing the cathedral early in the 21st century the diocese has 
launched a program to train young people from harlem and the south 
bronx in stone cutting and stone carving 
although it is a myth that cathedrals are never finished there 
are a number that have been unfinished for some time 
in philadelphia episcopalians broke ground in the 1920s for 
what was planned as the largest gothic cathedral in the world then 
the depression came along and there was a series of bishops who 
were concerned about the edifice complex said the rev tom 
mcclellan rector of st marys at the cathedral the parish church 
on the site 
all that was completed was the apse the front part of the 
church that includes the altar it is now part of st marys the 
diocese decided in 1975 to leave the cathedral unfinished and use 
the 100acre plot as a life care community for retired people 
in seattle ground was broken in 1930 for st marks episcopal 
cathedral there too the depression intervened the building has 
a wooden roof that was intended to be temporary and there has been 
rain damage in the sanctuary the exterior walls are a rough 
surface that was intended to be faced 
lisette trombley publications coordinator for the cathedral 
said a pledge campaign has been started to get the building 
finished starting with the roof 
 
