<TEXT>
when it comes to writing screenplays two cooks 
often come up with a better broth some of hollywoods biggest hits 
have been the result of collaboration between two or more writers 
and in todays electronic age sometimes the collaborators rarely 
see each other in person 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
rarely has a longdistance relationship been so 
blissful 
jim cash and jack epps jr havent seen one another in more than 
a year and have met just five times in the last 14 years they live 
2000 miles apart 
yet they are one of this towns hottest screenwriting teams 
authors of the summer hit dick tracy and the 1986 blockbuster 
top gun as well as legal eagles and the secret of my 
success 
in an industry where collaboration often is considered a 
necessary evil a disruption of ones personal vision cash and 
epps and several other screenwriting partnerships are finding that 
two cooks dont spoil the broth 
indeed as in a good marriage a writing teams sum frequently 
exceeds its parts 
cash works in east lansing mich where he teaches in the film 
program at michigan state university epps writes in culver city 
calif handling much of the teams hollywood business the former 
is good at dialogue while the latter specializes in story 
the two bridge the continental divide with an electronic meeting 
of the minds linked by speakerphone and dual computer screens 
flashing text simultaneously in two cities 
its words and music were good at different things epps 
says and i happen to like the distance its kept us together 
its taken ego out of the equation 
at a time when such actors as bruce willis and arnold 
schwarzenegger command salaries well in excess of 5 million the 
entertainment industry suddenly has rediscovered the value of 
scripts in recent weeks several screenplays have sold for 1 
million and more in frantic bidding wars many of these deals were 
prompted by teamwritten projects 
brian helgeland and manny coto reportedly received 1 million 
for their script ticking man doug richardson and rick jaffa 
collected the same amount for hell bent and back 
the ultimatum written by laurence dworet and robert roy 
pool brought them 1 million pen densham and john watson earned 
12 million for the script prince of thieves 
the ultimate test of a screenwriting team is not the price of a 
single script rather its whether the team can remain together 
consistently creating stories that please film critics and studio 
accountants 
these writers known simply by the names cash amp epps gale amp 
zemeckis gideon amp evans and ganz amp mandel can split 500000 and 
more per script the moneys good and sos the symbiotic link that 
makes the productivity pleasant 
writers feel that given the key role they play in filmmaking 
they dont draw enough credit when a picture flops they take the 
blame when its a smash someone else collects the credit whats 
more just about everybody from the electrician to the gaffer 
believes he or she can make a scene better than the most 
experienced writer 
since so much of the movie business hinges on compromise 
writers working in teams are prepared better for that giveandtake 
its a wonderful thing in life to be heard and understood and 
your partner is always there to hear and understand says lowell 
ganz his nineyear association with babaloo mandel has yielded 
scripts for parenthood the academy awardnominated splash 
cowritten with bruce jay friedman gung ho and night 
shift 
babaloo could go to mars and id wait for him to come back 
ganz says 
other teams joke that they have suicide pacts they cant face 
a blank page of paper alone writers block in a team is a rarity 
when one writer hits a wall the other should be able to take the 
lead 
rick natkin and partner david fuller wrote the scripts for last 
years hbo film the heist and next springs feature the 
taking of beverly hills starring ken wahl 
we entertain each other which makes the lonely task of 
writing so much easier natkin says we always write faster 
than an individual does 
a good writing team should spot a bomb even before the fuse is 
lit dialogue is read aloud plot points are debated and character 
development is argued among the more successful teams theres an 
unbreakable rule if one half of the team doesnt like what the 
other half suggests the idea goes to the dumpster 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900716-0180 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
writing teams tend to write less personal pieces but highly 
plotted pieces says producer lynda obst who cowrote the new 
hollywood novel dirty dreams with carol wolper their scripts 
have less internal logic less of an internal voice theyre not 
literary but they have an external logic that works in this 
business 
obst now making the fisher king with internal films are written 
by people who 
sit up late at night by themselves jim and i are pop writers 
writing for the masses 
some writing teams say differences of opinion rarely spark 
fights others say a bloodletting occasionally brings new life to 
the creative process billy wilders battles with charles brackett 
were legendary and golden the combative duo wrote oscarwinning 
scripts for 1945s the lost weekend and 1950s sunset 
boulevard written with dm marshman jr and the nominated 
script for 1948s a foreign affair written with richard breen 
weve had a lot of screaming says bruce evans whose 
12year association with raynold gideon has given birth to 
screenplays for stand by me an academy award nominee 
starman made in heaven a man a woman and a bank and 
the upcoming the day before midnight 
its very valuable having a partner disagree with you because 
if one partner can convince the other he can probably convince the 
audience too the end product outweighs the pain you have 
getting it like a good marriage evans says 
with most writing teams the screenwriting credit is shared 
evenly and some alternate the order in which their names appear 
the work however sometimes is not split justly 
michael beckner and jim gormans script for texas lead and 
gold recently sold in a deal valued at 1 million beckner is 
considered the writer of the team and gorman the producing partner 
writing little of the script 
novelist roger simon and directorwriter paul mazursky are 
listed as the writers for both enemies a love story and 
scenes from a mall a december release directed by mazursky 
starring woody allen and bette midler scenes from a mall is 
the first film allen has acted in but not directed since 1976s 
the front 
when mazursky works with a partner be it simon or leonidas 
capetanos he confers with his colleague outlining the story 
mazurskys partner then writes a first draft mazursky makes 
revisions to that draft and the process begins again with both 
writers sharing the keyboard 
its sort of like tagteam wrestling says simon im 
slightly more cerebral and hes slightly more theatrical 
although cash and epps work best many miles apart most writing 
teams find proximity improves the product 
ganz and mandel for instance who just finished a script for 
billy crystal titled city slickers sit across from each other 
in a small office before they begin writing their scripts in 
longhand they outline the story on a series of index cards the 
days work is typed up overnight which is reviewed the next 
morning and revised 
when we read what weve just written sometimes we weep 
sometimes we say were out of the business ganz said 
sometimes we dance together in the room 
