<TEXT>
it pains lawyernovelist scott f turow that 
some big city critics have dismissed his work as unimportant it 
hurts a lot until he looks at his bank balance the author of 
presumed innocent has learned to spin best sellers from his 
experiences as both a prosecutor and a defense attorney 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
as a prosecutor who turned defense attorney 
novelist scott f turow knows how to mine the shadowy regions of 
the legal profession 
in turows fiction prosecutors are violated and when the 
defense rests it may be in the bed of the clients mistress in 
turows real life judges have been jailed and yesterdays 
prosecutorial target may be todays client 
at age 41 turow now a partner in a major chicago law firm is 
twofortwo on the fiction bestseller lists reaping considerable 
national publicity and fat paychecks 
all i can say is they wont be holding any tag days for scott 
turow he said in a telephone interview while on tour promoting 
his second published novel burden of proof 
in 1986 turow stepped down after eight years as an assistant 
us attorney in chicago he got a record 200000 advance for his 
first published novel presumed innocent and watched it climb 
to the top of the hardbound bestseller lists that was followed by 
43 million paperback sales and a 1 million movie rights deal 
the 20 million movie starring harrison ford and directed by 
alan pakula recently opened 
the publicity surrounding presumed innocent made much of the 
fact that a highprofile prosecutor had written a thriller about a 
prosecutor being tried for murder it was not noted widely that 
turows only job since graduating from harvard law school had been 
with the us attorneys office which does not handle murder cases 
perhaps coincidentally the prosecutorasdefendant theme had 
appeared in one of turows own reallife cases that of 
thenillinois attorney gen william j scott turow was one of the 
federal attorneys who obtained a tax fraud conviction against the 
states chief prosecutor in 1980 
i realize now and i think my wife annette understood 
before i did that writing about the prosecution of a prosecutor 
was part of my preparation to do defense work turow said 
defense attorney phillip kurland argued in his unsuccessful 
appeal of scotts conviction that turow and his federal colleagues 
had turned the trial into a roman circus 
the phrase found a possibly subconscious echo in presumed 
innocent when hero rusty sabich likens his murder trial to 
christians and lions back in rome 
before leaving his federal post turow also saw more legal 
ambiguities through his involvement in operation greylord the 
federal probe that sent many cook county circuit court judges to 
prison 
the turn to defense work which coincided with the publication 
of presumed innocent brought turow to sonnenschein nath amp 
rosenthal a 300attorney firm with offices in six cities 
i suppose you could say im a specialist in whitecollar 
criminal defense mostly in the grand jury phase he said none 
of my clients are currently under indictment although several are 
under investigation 
ive walked both sides of the street now and i really can see 
the system from both sides 
turow once got a slap on the wrist from the 11th us circuit 
court of appeals in atlanta 
in 1987 a miami cocaine trafficking defendant named ronald 
ofshe sought to have his indictment dismissed because his defense 
attorney marvin glass was serving as a federal drug informant 
glass himself was a defendant in the chicago greylord probe and 
was negotiating with turow for leniency with turows permission 
glass had secretly taperecorded at least one of his conversations 
with ofshe 
although the appellate court refused to dismiss ofshes 
indictment it appended a footnote calling turows agreement with 
glass reprehensible and recommending that turow be investigated 
by attorney registration officials in chicago 
turows former superiors in the us justice department later 
exonerated him but the appeals court refused to strike the 
footnote from the record 
turow was asked if the incident may have been reflected in 
burden of proof in which the lawyerhero burglarizes his own 
clients house and also has a romantic scene in a hot tub with his 
prosecutorial adversary 
theres no doubt that that contributed to my analysis of the 
attorneyclient relationship turow said everything after 
all becomes fodder for the fictional mill in retrospect im just 
glad i could find something useful in something that was very 
painful and i still feel very unneccessary 
some critics have objected to the frequent sex scenes in 
burden of proof as unconvincing but the author says that only 
the ultimately platonic hottub tryst caused him problems 
i really had to work up my nerve to write it and submit it 
he said 
presumed innocent had its steamy scenes too but the 
critics found them more acceptable in what was at heart a 
traditional and gritty murder mystery 
one of the exalted things about the mystery novel is its 
architecture says turow who taught creative writing at stanford 
university before going to law school 
while at stanford turow says he made three serious attempts 
to get a novel published and once cranked out a novel in three 
weeks to win a bet 
im not sure i really won he says in retrospect 
turows first published book was one l a nonfiction 
account of his first year at harvard law school written on 
contract but he says his early unpublished works may have helped 
him escape the second novel jinx 
maybe my good fortune with my second novel was that it aint 
my second novel he says 
reviews of burden of proof although less enthusiastic than 
those for presumed innocent tended to be favorable with 
several critics suggesting it was a more serious work than its 
predecessor 
of course the bad ones hurt turow said of the reviews 
but theyve been running about 8 or 9to1 favorably i 
sometimes wonder if some of the negative reviewers arent out to 
get me but theres always that old lawyers adage reasonable 
minds can differ 
and then again no tag days 
</TEXT>
