<TEXT>
 
dmitri hvorostovksy sings tchaikovsky and verdi arias philips 
the rotterdam philharmonic orchestra conducted by valery gergiev 
compact disc 
 
a year ago no one had heard of dmitri hvorostovsky now on the 
strength of a few concerts the name of the 28yearold baritone 
from siberia is in the air as the next sensation about to hit major 
opera houses around the world 
is it all hype or is the fuss justified based on his first 
recording a collection of tchaikovsky and verdi arias its by no 
means hype 
he possesses a baritone voice of unusual beauty its a 
goodsize voice too one that should be capable of nicely filling 
even the biggest houses hes got phenomenal breath control 
spinning out the longest phrases with no apparent difficulty and 
hes an artist using his voice with considerable sensitivity and 
attention to the meaning of the words 
if theres a but its some doubt about his upper register 
which is impressive but doesnt have quite the same mellow sound as 
the rest of his voice it may be that it will fill out in time or 
it may be a sign of vocal dangers ahead 
hvorostovsky just 28 won the bbcs cardiff singer of the world 
competition last summer in a nationally televised performance he 
has since drawn ecstatic reviews for concerts at londons wigmore 
hall and at new yorks avery fisher hall and will soon be making 
opera debuts at covent garden la scala and san francisco 
his debut album is a collection of mostly familiar arias the 
biggest rarities are from tchaikovskys sorceress and 
iolanthe when it comes to the verdi hvorostovsky makes even 
the warhorses sound fresh the elder germonts di provenza il 
mar from la traviata for example 
great verdi baritones have been in short supply since the days 
of the late leonard warren and tito gobbi robert merrill and 
cornell macneil were among the best of his successors and now at 
last there may be another 
by mike silverman associated press writer 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
a round and a bout irs squeeze 
 
when squeeze came onto the pop scene more than a decade ago 
critics hailed songwriters chris difford and glenn tilbrook as 
their generations lennon and mccartney but record sales have 
failed to match squeezes lofty reputation and promising young 
songwriting teams today are rarely referred to as the new difford 
and tilbrook 
blame the fickle music marketplace because a round and a 
bout a live album of main squeeze favorites from as far back as 
1978 shows that difford and tilbrook lived up to their early 
billing these songs are terrific and its likely that if one of 
the older ones had broken into the top 40 others would have 
followed 
a round and a bout also shows that squeeze remains a 
topnotch act the band recorded at two concerts in january 
performs 15 songs with both respect for the original versions and a 
playfulness that puts a new twist on the arrangements 
given that squeeze has played about 900 concerts since 1974 
the date and site of each is listed in the liner notes its no 
surprise that the band is terrific live helping to make it that 
way are the diverse piano stylings of jools holland who has since 
left the band and some remarkable vocal harmonies particularly 
on black coffee in bed and hour glass milli vanilli this 
aint 
but the bands strength is the songs themselves one bright 
catchy melody gives way to another while the themes vary from the 
sublime up the junction to the ridiculous she doesnt have 
to shave 
a quibble because lead singers difford and tilbrook are 
difficult to understand their clever couplets are easy to miss 
the album should have included printed lyrics still for the many 
millions who have yet to buy their first squeeze record a round 
and a bout is a good primer 
by steven wine associated press writer 
</TEXT>
