<TEXT>
britains largest jewelry chain ratners plc said 
monday that it will stop selling jewelry made with south african 
gold after antiapartheid groups picketed its stores 
at least one of the groups end loans to south africa said it 
has suspended its action against ratners and has asked others to do 
the same pending a meeting with ratners officials in the next few 
days 
ratners which earlier this month made a friendly 328 million 
offer to acquire us jewelry retailer kay jewelers inc said its 
decision to stop using south african gold was part of a continuing 
switch to north american gold supplies 
south african gold is found in as much as 3 percent of its gold 
jewelry ratners said it had total sales of 16 billion in its 
fiscal year ended feb 3 
its a fairly simple process for us to remove the final few 
percentage points said a ratners spokesman who spoke on 
condition of anonymity the process should be completed in the next 
year or two he said 
the spokesman denied that the move was in reponse to 
antiapartheid pressure he said he believed only three of its more 
than 1000 british stores were picketed 
were a commercial organization not a political 
organization he said 
end loans to south africa said it and other groups had applied 
pressure on ratners in response to african national congress leader 
nelson mandelas call to intensify sanctions and boycott south 
african goods to end apartheid 
the anc is south africas leading black opposition movement it 
is seeking to end white minority rule of south africas black 
majority 
ratners has purchased much of its gold jewelry supplies from 
italy which according to a us general accounting office report 
gets 91 percent of its gold fom south africa the group said 
south africa produces onethird of the worlds gold the group 
said south african supplies dominate the european gold market and 
almost all gold jewelry sold in britain is made with south african 
gold the group said 
nonsouth african supplies of gold are plentiful it said 
this historic victory will send clear signals to south africa 
and will hasten an early end to apartheid said cosmas desmond 
head of end loans to south africa it shows that british business 
can no longer avoid the moral implications of collaborating with 
apartheid 
