<TEXT>
health care cost issues will take up a 
lot of time in this summers auto industry labor negotiations a 
ford motor co executive said monday 
health care is just a megaissue said the executive who 
spoke only on condition of anonymity 
ford has three bargaining priorities during talks with the 
united auto workers union improving vehicle quality holding down 
costs and getting the union to agree to flexibility in how cars are 
made 
the union has said protecting current jobs for its members is 
the top bargaining priority for each of the automakers 
improvements in pensions wages and health care benefits follow 
negotiations between the uaw and ford open thursday talks 
between the union and general motors corp open wednesday chrysler 
corp and the uaw open talks friday uaw contracts with each of the 
big three expire sept 14 
the ford executive estimated his company pays about 4200 
annually in health care for each of its 175000 active and retired 
employees thats less than chryslers 4600 for its approximately 
60000 workers and slightly more than the 3800 a year that gm 
pays for each of its 400000 unionized workers 
automakers long have complained their health care costs put them 
in a hole compared with japanese companies making cars and trucks 
in the united states the average age of uaw workers at the big 
three is about 42 years the estimated average age of a worker in 
the so called transplant companies is in the mid to upper20s 
chrysler chief negotiator anthony st john has said simply 
continuing the current level of companypaid health benefits for 
its workers would add 16 percent to chryslers labor costs 
automakers and the union have been looking for ways to cut 
healthcare costs while maintaining benefits one is for employees 
to switch from traditional healthcare coverage such as blue cross 
and blue shield to health maintenance organizations or preferred 
provider organizations 
there is no doubt that the hmos are a cost savings the ford 
executive said thirty percent to 40 percent of uawcovered 
employees at the big three are members of hmos or ppos 
another expensive issue will be how to get cost of living 
protection for uaw retirees whose numbers nearly equal the unions 
active big three membership of about 500000 
union leaders are being pressured by the retirees to push for 
costofliving protection keyed to the inflation rate both sides 
say that could cost billions of dollars 
maybe the clue to pensions is what has been done in the last 
couple of agreements the ford executive said lumpsum payments 
