<TEXT>
the white house hiked its forecast of next 
years budget deficit to 1688 billion on monday 2314 billion 
if savings and loan costs are counted and warned of devastating 
cuts in programs without a quick budget compromise with congress 
the new estimate was more than twothirds higher than the 
administrations projection just six months ago 
airport control towers could be closed student loans canceled 
food inspections interrupted and military forces halved by cutting 
perhaps one million people as the government buckled under what 
could be over 100 billion in automatic cuts this october said 
budget director richard darman 
it seemed unlikely that congress would permit cuts on such a 
huge scale and white house officials conceded that easing was 
needed in the nations deficitreduction law which mandates 
spending cuts across a broad range of programs if targets for 
reducing federal red ink are not met 
but administration officials insisted they would support a 
watering down of the grammrudman budgetbalancing law only if 
coupled with a 50 billion package of spending cuts and new taxes 
twomonthold budget summit talks between the administration 
and congressional leaders on a deficitreduction package have 
seemed bogged down despite president bushs reversal of his no 
new taxes pledge three weeks ago 
house budget committee chairman leon panetta dcalif said the 
consequences of a 100 billion grammrudman cut would be so severe 
that the budget negotiators must somehow work out a deal 
the crisis is real panetta told reporters these numbers 
should hit the white house congress and the summit like a fire 
alarm in the middle of the night 
however senate budget committee chairman james sasser dtenn 
said the numbers were nothing new and he contended the talks were 
stalled because of a lack of leadership from bush he called on the 
president to address the nation explaining the extent of the 
budget problem laying out his solution and explaining the 
consequences of failure 
the ranking republican on the senate budget committee pete 
domenici rnm said the new deficit figures would serve as a 
warning to any lawmakers who want the budget talks to fail and to 
those he said are making ultimatums 
mondays revised deficit projection was up 10 billion from the 
administrations informal estimate just a month ago and up sharply 
from januarys 1005 billion estimate 
the new figures contained in the administrations annual 
midyear economic review are based on the economic data that show 
slower economic growth than the administration expected the white 
house now projects that the economy will grow by only 22 percent 
this year down from the 26 percent it predicted in january 
in gloomy remarks that appeared directed partly at congressional 
budget negotiators darman spoke of acrosstheboard spending 
reductions of a totally unprecedented size if the 100 billion 
gap cant be bridged by a budget compromise 
added treasury secretary nicholas brady this problem is 
serious the law is the law and were going to obey it this 
is not a political wrestling match 
president bush issued a written statement saying that in light 
of the revised deficit estimate it is therefore all the more 
important that the budget summit reach agreement promptly and 
congress act responsibly to bring the deficit down 
any cuts under the grammrudman law would be split 5050 between 
domestic and military spending if bush decides to include military 
personnel in the defense cuts one million men and women could be 
removed from government payrolls about half the force darman said 
he gave these other examples of prospective cuts 
massive layoffs of air traffic controllers and the closing of 
100 airport control towers forcing sharp reductions in commercial 
flights and an increase in traveler delays of 400 to 600 
percent 
a halt to all new cleanups of toxic waste sites 
elimination of pell grants to 12 million college students 
a 40 percent reduction in head start enrollment for 
preschoolers from poor families 
a 140day curtailment of meat and poultry inspections sharply 
reducing the supply of these products in supermarkets and driving 
up prices 
sharp cuts in programs involving childrens vaccinations the 
elderly the war on drugs and prisons 
despite darmans warnings few in the administration appeared to 
believe that cuts of the scope of 100 billion would actually be 
seen 
michael boskin chairman of the white house council of economic 
advisers told reporters that cuts in excess of 50 billion in one 
year could be destabilizing and possibly tip the economy into a 
recession 
boskin said to win the administrations support for a partial 
easing of the grammrudman targets congress must agree to a 
successful multiyear enforceable deficit reduction plan 
figuring in the 1991 costs of rescuing the troubled savings and 
loan industry would add 626 billion to the total federal 1991 
deficit bringing it to a projected 2314 billion the 
administration said 
there is considerable sentiment both in congress and the 
administration to keep the costs of the savings and loan bailout 
out of the official budget calculations 
the administration blamed the sharp deterioration in the deficit 
from january until now on the higherthanexpected sampl bailout and 
weaker economic growth that cuts into government revenues it also 
cited higher interest rates that boost the cost of servicing the 
nations 3 trillion national debt 
the omb projected a 48 percent rise in consumer prices this 
year matching last yearsinflation increase but up from the 
administrations estimate of a lower inflation figure of 44 
percent 
and it raised the governments projected cost of shortterm 
borrowing shortterm by a full percentage point to 77 percent 
