<TEXT>
a judge on monday tossed out all charges 
against rite aid corp and its president after ruling the evidence 
against them in a bribery case was circumstantial 
martin l grass 36 and rite aid were accused of bribing a 
member of ohios board of pharmacy to resign so the panel would 
have a makeup more favorable to the drugstore company 
cuyahoga county common pleas judge lillian greene granted a 
defense motion asking for a judgment of acquittal after the 
prosecution rested its case 
greene said prosecution evidence was circumstantial and did not 
substantiate a case of willful intent to bribe 
some of the spectators in the courtroom gallery applauded and 
several hugged the smiling grass and congratulated him 
grass said he was sure he would be found innocent 
i never had a doubt it was a ridiculous prosecution he 
said 
grass and rite aid based in shiremanstown pa were charged in 
an indictment unsealed in august with bribery and possession of 
criminal tools described as a corporate aircraft 
both charges are felonies the bribery charge is punishable by 
up to 10 years in prison and a maximum fine of 5000 the 
possession of criminal tools charge carries a maximum sentence of 
five years and a fine up to 2500 
grass was accused of trying to bribe pharmacy board member 
melvin wilczynski 61 to step down so a new board member more to 
rite aids liking could be appointed 
grass gave wilczynski a check worth more than 33000 the 
defense had argued the payment was in fact a legal buyout of 
wilczynskis consulting contract for another drug store company 
lane drug co a division of peoples drug stores inc acquired by 
rite aid last year 
during the trial which began july 9 prosecutors contended that 
grass offered the buyout only on condition that wilczynski step 
down as a voting member of the board the government said rite aid 
had complained the pharmacy board harassed the company when 
enforcing state regulations over drugstores 
defense attorneys have said the state pharmacy board had a 
vendetta against rite aid because it challenged some rules and 
decisions which it thought were unreasonable 
the prosecutors had the jury hear and watch two secretlymade 
tapes a recorded telephone conversation between wilczynski and 
grass on april 26 1989 and a videotape the following day in a 
hotel room near cleveland hopkins international airport 
grass was arrested at the hotel room 
in the telephone tape wilczynski is heard arranging the 
followingday meeting with grass at the hotel to discuss the 
contract buyout and rite aids provision of health insurance after 
the buyout 
in the videotape wilczynski and grass are seen in the motel 
room leafing through papers some of which wilczynski signs 
prosecutors said the papers included six undated letters of 
resignation addressed to ohio gov richard celeste from which 
wilczynski was supposed to select for signing 
wilczynski remains a voting member of the pharmacy board which 
oversees drugstores adherence to state rules 
celeste has said he knew of no plans to get any rite aid 
officials or supporters appointed to the pharmacy board 
before the trial began greene dismissed as evidence three other 
taped conversations which the prosecution wanted to use the judge 
said they were made by pharmacy board investigators who did not 
have jurisdiction in the criminal case the two tapes that were 
allowed were made by cuyahoga county sheriffs officers 
</TEXT>
