<TEXT>
supporters of a balanced budget amendment to 
the constitution said monday they were short of the votes needed to 
win house passage 
were not doing as well as id hoped right now said rep 
charles stenholm dtexas 
however stenholm said he and other supporters were lobbying 
hard and expected to come closer than ever tuesday to the required 
twothirds majority 
president bush sent a letter to capitol hill urging support of 
the amendment and calling for a lineitem veto and greater 
authority for the president to impound funds 
together with political courage and discipline these tools 
are vital to solving the problem of budget deficits bush said 
he called the balanced budget amendment crucial to our nations 
longterm economic health and properity 
stenholm prime democratic sponsor of the amendment said he was 
about 18 votes short of victory but that there were enough 
undecided votes to put it over the top 
the amendment if approved by a twothirds vote of the congress 
and threefourths of the states would ban the government from 
spending more than it takes in unless threefifths of the congress 
voted to waive the requirement 
the balanced budget rules would not take effect before fiscal 
1993 and would be set aside in time of war 
rep joe barton rtexas said he would try to change the 
amendment to require a supermajority vote also to raise taxes 
above the rate of growth in national income 
the house last voted on a balanced budget amendment in 1982 it 
fell short by more than 40 votes 
the house democratic leadership opposes the amendment 
members as always are trying to reach for simple answers to 
what are very tough problems said rep leon panetta dcalif 
chairman of the house budget committee ive never seen a process 
change in the world that is going to produce the courage and guts 
you need to make tough choices 
some of my colleagues will find it a refuge he said i 
think we have a very good chance of beating the amendment 
</TEXT>
