<TEXT>
the commodities trading firm headed by chicago 
board of trade chairman karsten mahlmann said monday it is seeking 
an outside investor and parceling out some accounts to get its 
books in order 
the firm stotler and co has been directed by the board of 
trade to bring its amount of cashonhand up to 4 percent of 
customer funds as required by the commodity futures trading 
commission by the close of business wednesday according to a 
statement issued by the firms parent company stotler group inc 
if a brokerage does not maintain the required amount of capital 
the exchange can restrict the brokerage to trading only for the 
purpose of liquidation and can transfer that brokerages customer 
accounts to other firms said michael oconnell a board of trade 
spokesman 
he referred questions about the specifics of the case to 
chicagobased stotler group where spokesman vito piazza declined 
to comment beyond the prepared statement 
the statement said stotler planned to meet the requirement by 
transferring a portion of its customer accounts and stake in the 
market to other brokerages and by seeking a capital infusion from 
various parties 
the moves are likely to reduce the firms revenue and net 
income stotler said 
without a capital infusion stotler group may be unable to 
meet its debt obligations unless those obligations are refinanced 
or restructured the company said 
the chicago tribune reported saturday that stotler one of the 
nations 10 biggest futures brokerages may have run afoul of 
capital requirements because of its recent rapid growth 
stotler group said another subsidiary brokerage rg dickinson 
amp co of des moines iowa was not affected by the compliance 
problems at stotler and co 
mahlman is serving his fourth consecutive oneyear term as 
chairman of the bot stotler is one of the nations 10 largest 
futures brokers 
