<TEXT>
an outside examiner appointed by a federal 
bankruptcy judge to look into the 1986 junkbond financed buyout of 
revco ds inc said monday he believes successful lawsuits could 
arise from the deal 
however the examiner barry l zaretsky said lawsuits should 
not be filed to avoid interfering with bankruptcy court proceedings 
our preliminary finding that the revco leveraged buyout 
amounted to a fraudulent conveyance is likely to lead to greater 
scrutiny of the financial condition of junk bondfinanced deals 
said zaretsky who was appointed examiner by us bankruptcy court 
judge harold f white last month 
zaretsky said his examination has not found actual fraud but 
that the deal was made with either fraudulent intent or without 
fair consideration of whether the company could pay its debts 
the examiner also said state law tort claims and other actions 
could arise from the buyout 
zaretsky is a brooklyn law school professor and counsel to the 
new yorkbased law firm of kelly drye amp warren 
revco went from a publicly held company to a private one during 
a 15 billion managementled leveraged buyout 
the revco buyout failed in 1988 revcos was the first major 
debtfinanced buyout to seek protection from creditors under 
chapter 11 of federal bankruptcy laws 
this year the suburban clevelandbased drugstore chain one of 
the countrys largest decided to sell more than 700 of its 2000 
stores in order to concentrate on eastern operations where sales 
are strongest 
the appointment of an examiner was requested by us trustee 
conrad j morgenstern who supervised the revco bankruptcy case 
</TEXT>
